>perspective.
 
yes, i'm not intending to actively limit anything, just wishing to explore
what the limits have tended to be, if anything.
 
 
>responding to Michael Coffey:
>
>> clearly, some writing involves the body more than other writing; henry
>> miller vs henry james, for example.
>
>writing *about* the body is not what's meant, I think
 
yes, fred, i think that's exactly it.  er, not it.
 
>mouth, and/or feeling language rhythms as body rhythms,
>is one way to write to my body; not the only one, I
 
see, here's where all this starts to get very, very tricky.  is "writing
through the body" ala cixous the same as "to write my body"?  seems to me
that there is a very subtle and very important difference that i can't
quite figure (hence my original question) between writing through the body
and writing the body.
 
emily:
 
> So, is
>there anyone out there willing & able to articulate the distinctions between
>these 2 or 3 phrases?  And possibly give examples?  My body would be
>grateful, or else I would.
 
i second the question.
 
eryque
