From:         David Baratier <dave.baratier@MOSBY.COM>
Subject:      Creeley's Orpheus
 
     If you are interested in defining writing through the body in the
     manner that Charles Alexander suggests, one that is multi-valent, I
     would suggest _Just Whistle_ by C.D. Wright. If you find language to
     be an artifice, as Henry Gould suggests, or at least artificial enough
     to deem an acknowledgement necessary then I'd start out with Toril
     Moi, preferably Sexual Textual Politics as a primer for some of the
     universal definitions inherent in the word body's semiotic screen.
 
     Be Well.
 
     David Baratier
