as one who loves nothing more than to stir up finally stilled waters, I
remind all readers of the following lines from Kerouac's possibly
postmodern novel _Desolation Angels_:
 
it's Gia Vlaencia, the daughter of the mad Spanish anthropologist sage
who'd lived with the Pomo and Pit River Indians of California, famous old
man, whom I'd read and revered only three years ago while working the
railroad outa San Louis Obispo--
                                   (pg. 138)
 
Possible first instance of direct influence of Pomo culture on postmodern
culture?
