Subject:      Re: sometimes a formal Finch comes
 
John Cage is inevitably mentioned. He once said to me that after
he had heard any piece of his more than once, it began to sound
melodic! Eric Mottram's response when I told him this was that
the human brain is inherently incapable of producing something
which is formless. Which is why Cage didn't like improvisation;
he said it was too predictable.
 
John Whiting
Diatribal Press
London
