Date:         Tue, 28 May 1996 13:46:44 -0400
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         David Kellogg <kellogg@ACPUB.DUKE.EDU>
Subject:      Re: interesting/boring journals
In-Reply-To:  <Pine.SUN.3.93.960524223424.26389F-100000@elaine30.Stanford.EDU>
 
On Fri, 24 May 1996, Marjorie Perloff wrote:
 
> journals like Sulfur,
> Language, Poetics Journal, Talisman, etc etc. aren't sponsored by
> university presses, don't pretend to be run by an "editorial collective"
> and all that.
 
Right.  The type of journal makes all the difference.  The inside cover of
Social Text has all the apparatus of a peer-reviewed journal (submit
essays in triplicate to such-and-such address in this form), and there's
in fact nothing to indicate otherwise.  (Nor to indicate that you're
probably wasting your time, since everything's solicited anyway).
 
Seriously now: all of us can tell the difference between Talisman and
Contemporary Literature, and the fact that Talisman happens to be livelier
doesn't meant that CL should stop being peer-reviewed.  With regard to
Social Text, Ross's claim that the journal isn't peer reviewed is an
obvious attempt to escape responsibilty for publishing an article that
nobody on the board (or collective) cared to engage seriously.
 
Cheers,
David
