Date:         Thu, 30 May 1996 20:53:05 -0700
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         Thomas Bell <tbjn@WELL.COM>
Subject:      Re: Russian/American sonnet quiddity
In-Reply-To:  <v01520d02add3c1f2a6e6@[166.84.199.56]>
 
After a desultory time as an English major, I date the beginning of
my positive experiences with poetry to the early 60's when I was
able to read Russian.  I found the early work of Yevtushenko and
Vosnesensky. This led in many directions, but I think the fascination
was related to a comment made on this list a few days ago about the
Russian poetry festival.  I deleted this (and would appreciate a copy
sent) but the general idea was that the difference between American
and Russian poetry was that American poetry was a carefully constructed
experience (whether formal or experimental) while Russian poetry began
with the experience.
 
This is consistent with my experience even if I or the poster of the
comment might not be using words that adequately describe the
difference.  I feel there is a difference and that the difference is
related to the current form discussion.  If anyone understands what
I am talking about I would appreciate hearing from them either here
or offlist.
 
Thanks
Tom Bell
